[
    {
        "content": "<p>How do you call a 2-category which is actually a 1-category? I mean, everyone of its hom-cats is actually a set and composition is unital and associative on the nose</p>",
        "id": 249958991,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1629363267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>2-discrete?</p>",
        "id": 249962174,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1629365514
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or perhaps 1-truncated.</p>",
        "id": 249962261,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1629365568
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Locally discrete?</p>",
        "id": 249962262,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1629365568
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That makes sense but then it becomes a pain for higher categories surely because you need to keep nesting the 'locally'</p>",
        "id": 249962555,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1629365785
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How about: a 1-category?</p>",
        "id": 249966360,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1629368539
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We often use the adjective <em>degenerate</em> in  the case of other sorts of rankings.</p>",
        "id": 249977024,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Awbrey",
        "timestamp": 1629375242
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"Locally discrete\" is the standard terminology for 2-categories.  For generalizations to higher categories, one would go with something numerically indexed like \"1-truncated\".</p>",
        "id": 249993727,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1629382978
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll go with 1-truncated, makes sense :)</p>",
        "id": 249999928,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1629385618
    }
